The storm howled against the stained-glass windows of Blackwood Manor, throwing long, distorted shadows across the stone floor of the library. Marianne sat by the hearth, the firelight casting a warm, crimson glow over her face. In her lap lay a letter, its ink slightly smudged by rain or tears, she could no longer tell. The words were written in a sharp, elegant hand she knew all too well.

"Do not look for me, Marianne," the letter read. "There are secrets in this house that are not meant for the light. My love for you is a poison, and if you stay, it will consume you just as it has consumed me."

A floorboard creaked behind her. She did not startle; she had grown accustomed to the ghosts of the manor, both real and imagined. She turned slowly to find Julian standing in the doorway, his coat wet with rain, his dark eyes reflecting the dying embers of the fire.

"You should have left when the gates were still open," Julian said, his voice low, like the rumble of distant thunder.

"I cannot leave," Marianne whispered, rising to face him. "You know that as well as I do. My heart is bound to these walls, and to you, regardless of the shadow that hangs over your name."

Julian stepped into the room, the scent of damp earth and crushed roses clinging to him. He reached out, his fingers brushing her cheek, cold as ice but feather-light. "We are dancing on the edge of an abyss, Marianne. The family curse is not a myth; it is a living thing, waiting in the dark."

"Then let it take us," she replied, pressing her hand over his. "I would rather burn in the dark with you than live in a world without your shadow."
